Understanding Chicago's Demographic Characteristics

Matthew Grady

July 10, 2021

Overview

In this work sample, I'll use R to access and visualize demographic data for the City of Chicago. Here's my plan:

  • I'll use the tidycensus package to access demographic data from the U.S. Census Bureau's American Community Survey (ACS)1;
  • I'll use a bar plot to summarize the City's racial composition; and
  • I'll create a choropleth map to show how Chicago's largest racial groups are distributed across the city;
  • I'll use a diversity index to identify racially diverse, and racially homogeneous neighborhoods; and
  • I'll explore diversity in two of Chicago's most diverse community areas: West Ridge and Hyde Park.

Before getting started, I'll load some R packages and some fonts I plan to use.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(tigris)
library(rgdal)
library(stringr)
library(gridExtra)
library(extrafont)
library(sf)
library(rgeos)
library(ggrepel)
loadfonts(device = "win", quiet = TRUE)

Getting the American Commmunity Survey (ACS) Data

First, I'd like to create a bar plot to show Chicago's racial composition. To do so, I'll access demographic data from the ACS using the tidycensus package.

Using the code below, I'll request population estimates, by race, for every census designated place in Illinois. Then, I'll subset data for the City of Chicago. I'll request 2015-2019 five-year estimates, which are based on data collected over a five-year period.

city.dem = get_acs(geography = "place", 
              table="B03002",   # The table with the race data
              state = c('IL'),
              survey = 'acs5',  # ACS, 5-year estimates
              year = 2019)

city.dem = city.dem %>%
  filter(NAME %in% c('Chicago city, Illinois'))  # subset Chicago

For this analysis, I'll create a new race variable by classifying residents into the following mutually exclusive groups:

  • White (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Black or African American (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • American Indian and Alaska Native (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Asian (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Some other race (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Two or more races (not Hispanic or Latino)
  • Hispanic or Latino

Going forward, I'll drop the "not Hispanic or Latino" phrase from the group names.

city.dem = city.dem %>%
  filter(variable %in% c('B03002_001','B03002_003','B03002_004','B03002_005',
                         'B03002_006','B03002_007','B03002_008','B03002_009',
                         'B03002_012')) %>%
  mutate(race = as.factor(recode(variable,
    B03002_001="Total",
    B03002_003="White",
    B03002_004="Black or African American",
    B03002_005="American Indian and Alaska Native",
    B03002_006="Asian",
    B03002_007="Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander",
    B03002_008="Some other race",
    B03002_009="Two or more races",
    B03002_012="Hispanic or Latino")
  ))

For plotting purposes, I'll retain the groups that make up at least one percent of the Chicago population.

city.dem = city.dem %>%
  mutate(Percent = estimate / estimate[race=='Total']*100) %>%
  filter(Percent >= 1 & race != 'Total')

Next, I'll order the levels of the race variable based on group size, and create some nicely formatted labels that I'll use when I create the bar plot.

city.dem$race = factor(city.dem$race, levels=c('White','Black or African American','Hispanic or Latino',
                                               'Asian','Two or more races'))

city.dem$labels = paste(as.character(round(city.dem$Percent, 0)), '%', sep='')

Chicago's Racial Distribution

bar.plot.dem = ggplot(city.dem, aes(x=race, y=Percent, fill=race)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", color='gray70', size=1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c('#F8766D','#7CAE00','#C77CFF','#00BFC4','#F564E3')) +

                                       'Asian','Two or more\nraces')) +
  geom_text(aes(label=labels), vjust=-.5, size=4, family='Segoe UI', color='gray20') +
  labs(title="Chicago has roughly equal numbers of White, Black, and Latinx residents",
       subtitle="Distribution of Race in the City of Chicago",
       caption = "\n\nSource: American Community Survey, 2015-2019 five-year estimates.")

Next, I'll create a choropleth map that shows how Chicago's largest racial groups are distributed across the city. I'll start by using the tidycensus package to get population estimates, by race, for census tracts within the two Illinois counties that overlap with the City of Chicago boundary: Cook and DuPage counties. I'll use the same basic code as before, except that I'll specify "tract" as the desired geographic level.

tract.dem = get_acs(geography = "tract",  # Get tract-level data
              table = "B03002",  
              year = 2019,  
              survey = 'acs5',
              state = 'IL', 
              county = c('Cook','DuPage'))

Next, I'll create my own race variable in the same way that I did before.

tract.dem = tract.dem %>%
  filter(variable %in% c('B03002_001','B03002_003','B03002_004','B03002_005',
                         'B03002_006','B03002_007','B03002_008','B03002_009',
                         'B03002_012')) %>%
  mutate(race = as.factor(recode(variable,
                                 B03002_001="Total",
                                 B03002_003="White",
                                 B03002_004="Black or African American",
                                 B03002_005="American Indian and Alaska Native",
                                 B03002_006="Asian",
                                 B03002_007="Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander",
                                 B03002_008="Some other race",
                                 B03002_009="Two or more races",
                                 B03002_012="Hispanic or Latino")
  ))

Now, I'll calculate each group's share of each census tract's population. Then I'll identify the largest group in each tract. I'll use this information when I create the choropleth map.

tract.dem.largest = tract.dem %>%
  group_by(GEOID) %>%
  mutate(race.pct=estimate / estimate[race=='Total']*100) %>%
  filter(race != 'Total') %>%
  select(GEOID, race, estimate, race.pct) %>%
  slice(which.max(estimate))

In order to create the chorpleth map, I need to get census tract shape files for Cook and DuPage counties. I'll access these shape files from the Census Bureau using the tigris package.

Cook.tracts = tracts(state = 'IL', county='Cook', cb=F, progress_bar=F, class='sp')
DuPage.tracts = tracts(state = 'IL', county='DuPage', cb=F, progress_bar=F, class='sp')

tracts = rbind(Cook.tracts, DuPage.tracts)

The census tract shape files cover the entire area of Cook and DuPage counties. Because I want to limit the map to Chicago only, I'll need to trim the county census tract shape file. To do this, I'll first need to input the Chicago boundary shape file, which I retrieved from the City of Chicago Data Portal2.

chi = readOGR("C:/Users/Matt/Desktop/IL shape files/Chicago", "Chicago shape file", verbose=F)

Next, I'll change the coordinate reference system for the Chicago shape file. Then, I'll use the intersect command from the raster package to trim the county census tract shape file along the city boundary.

chi.sf = st_as_sf(chi)
chi.sf = st_transform(chi.sf, "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84")
chi = as(chi.sf, 'Spatial')
chi.fort = fortify(chi, region='name') # fortify the shape file

library(raster)
crs(chi) = crs(tracts)
chi.tracts = intersect(tracts, chi)
detach("package:raster", unload=TRUE)

Now, I'll limit the data frame with the census tract demographic data to include only tracts that are fully or partially within Chicago. Then, I'll add the demographic data to the census tract shape file. Note that I've also created a fortified version of the shape file, which I'll use to create the choropleth map with ggplot.

tract.dem.largest = tract.dem.largest[tract.dem.largest$GEOID %in% chi.tracts$GEOID,]

chi.tracts.fort = fortify(chi.tracts, region='GEOID')

tract.dem.largest$id = tract.dem.largest$GEOID
tr2 = merge(chi.tracts.fort, tract.dem.largest, by='id', all.x=T, all.y=F)
tr2 = tr2[order(tr2$order),]

Finally, I'll categorize each tract based on its largest racial group. I'll highlight a tract if its largest group makes up more than 75% of its population. I'll also identify tracts that contain no residents.

tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'White' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'White >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'White' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'White < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Black or African American' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Black >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Black or African American' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Black < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Hispanic or Latino' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Latino >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Hispanic or Latino' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Latino < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Asian' & tr2$race.pct >= 75] = 'Asian >= 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$race == 'Asian' & tr2$race.pct < 75] = 'Asian < 75%'
tr2$cat3[tr2$estimate ==0] = 'No residents'

tr2$cat3 = factor(tr2$cat3, levels=c('White < 75%','White >= 75%','Black < 75%','Black >= 75%',
                                     'Latino < 75%','Latino >= 75%','Asian < 75%','Asian >= 75%','No residents'))

Exploring Racial Diversity

The ... The diversity index represents the probability that two people randomly drawn from the census tract will be of different races.

I'll start by calculating the racial diversity index for each census tract in Cook and DuPage counties. I'll use the same racial categories I established earlier.

tract.dem = tract.dem %>%
  group_by(GEOID) %>%
  mutate(race.pct = estimate / estimate[race=='Total']*100) %>%
  filter(race != 'Total')

tract.div = tract.dem %>%
  group_by(GEOID) %>%
  mutate(race.pct2 = race.pct^2) %>%
  summarize(same = sum(race.pct2),
            same.pct = same / 10000,
            diff.pct = 1-same.pct)

Next, I'll limit the data set to include census tracts in the City of Chicago.

tract.div = tract.div[tract.div$GEOID %in% chi.tracts$GEOID,]

tract.div$id = tract.div$GEOID
tr3 = merge(chi.tracts.fort, tract.div, by='id', all.x=T, all.y=F)
tr3 = tr3[order(tr3$order),]

Now, I'll categorize the tracts based on the diversity index.

tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .10] = '.00 to .09'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .10 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .20] = '.10 to .19'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .20 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .30] = '.20 to .29'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .30 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .40] = '.30 to .39'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .40 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .50] = '.40 to .49'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .50 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .60] = '.50 to .59'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .60 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .70] = '.60 to .69'
tr3$div.group[round(tr3$diff.pct,2) >= .70 & round(tr3$diff.pct,2) < .80] = '.70 to .79'

                           tract.dem$GEOID %in% hp.tract.ids,]

div.dem = div.tract.dem %>%
  group_by(neighborhood, race) %>%
  summarize(Sum = sum(estimate)) %>%
  mutate(pct = Sum / sum(Sum)*100) %>%
  filter(pct >= 1)
